{
  "answer": "**In the final maqta (signature couplet) of ghazal 80 from Mirza Ghalib's *Diwan-e-Ghalib*, the poet states:**\n\n> Hum ko maaloom hai jannat ki haqeeqat lekin  \n> Dil ke khush rakhne ko Ghalib yeh khayaal achha hai[^1]\n\n**English translation:**  \n\"We know the truth of heaven, anyway;  \nBut Ghalib, for the heart's sake, let us say this thought is a fine thing.\"[^1]\n\nGhalib conveys that he is fully aware of the **true reality (haqeeqat) of paradise (jannat)**—implying it may not live up to idealized religious or poetic expectations—but he still finds the comforting **idea or fancy (khayaal)** of it valuable, as it soothes the heart (dil). This reflects his characteristic blend of skepticism, irony, and humanism, prioritizing emotional consolation over literal truth.[^1]\n\n[^1]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, [paragraph](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/80-husn-e-mah-garche-ba-hangaam-e-kamaal-achha-hai/translation/#p-7c74eb).",
